#!/usr/bin/env ssc
---
name: v2-db-url-scheme-not-jdbc
description: v2 databases-frontmatter parser only recognizes url schemes literally prefixed "jdbc:"
backends: [int]
databases:
  mydb:
    url: "sqlite::memory:"
---

# v2 `databases:` front-matter parser drops non-`jdbc:` URL schemes

busi's `databases:` convention is the `sqlite:` scheme (`sqlite::memory:`,
`sqlite:./data.db`, `sqlite:${env:VAR}` — see v1's own
JsGenSqlBlockTest/WasmBackendSqlTest, which pin this as the FIRST-CLASS,
tested convention alongside `jdbc:`). v1's real front-matter handling
resolves it fine on every backend.

v2's ad hoc line-by-line parser (FrontendBridge.parseDatabasesFromFrontmatter)
only calls `PluginBridge.registerDb` when `rawUrl.startsWith("jdbc:")` — any
other scheme is silently skipped (no warning; the `if` guard is a no-op, not
a caught failure). At runtime `Db.query`/`Db.execute` then hits
`MinimalCtx.dbConnect`, finds nothing registered, and crashes:
`RuntimeException: No database registered for 'mydb' — add a databases:
section to front-matter` — even though the front-matter IS present and
correct. Repro: `bin/ssc --v2 tests/conformance/v2-db-url-scheme-not-jdbc.ssc`
(v1 lanes below pin the correct, passing behavior).

Found 2026-07-09 minimizing busi's `repo_sqlite_index` v2-sweep failure
(`url: "sqlite::memory:"` in tests/v2/repo_sqlite_index.ssc).

```scalascript
Db.execute("mydb", "create table t(x int)", [])
Db.execute("mydb", "insert into t values (1)", [])
val rows = Db.query("mydb", "select x from t", [])
println(rows.length)
```
